04568nam a22006855i 9781501711473DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017114737 a10.7591/97815017114732doi  a(DE-B1597)503448  a(OCoLC)1038484987  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKLA40.P64W66 2005 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a345.47/02311 aWood, Elizabeth A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerforming Justice :bAgitation Trials in Early Soviet Russia /cElizabeth A. Wood. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b2 tables, 22 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Question Of Origins -- t2. Experimental Trials In The Red Army, 1919-20 -- t3. The Trial Of Lenin -- t4. Teaching Politics Through Trials, 1921-23 -- t5. The Culture Of Everyday Life, 1922-24 -- t6. Melodrama In The Service Of Science -- t7. The Trial Of The New Woman -- t8. The Crisis In The Clubs And The Erosion Of The Public Sphere -- t9. Shaming The Boys Who Smoke Cigarettes -- t10. Fiction Becomes Indistinguishable From Reality, 1928-33 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tArchives Consulted -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter seizing power in 1917, the Bolshevik regime faced the daunting task of educating and bringing culture to the vast and often illiterate mass of Soviet soldiers, workers, and peasants. As part of this campaign, civilian educators and political instructors in the military developed didactic theatrical fictions performed in workers' and soldiers' clubs in the years from 1919 to 1933. The subjects addressed included politics, religion, agronomy, health, sexuality, and literature. The trials were designed to permit staging by amateurs at low cost, thus engaging the citizenry in their own remaking. In reconstructing the history of the so-called agitation trials and placing them in a rich social context, Elizabeth A. Wood makes a major contribution to rethinking the first decade of Soviet history. Her book traces the arc by which a regime's campaign to educate the masses by entertaining and disciplining them culminated in a policy of brute shaming.Over the course of the 1920s, the nature of the trials changed, and this process is one of the main themes of the later chapters of Wood's book. Rather than humanizing difficult issues, the trials increasingly made their subjects (alcoholics, boys who smoked, truants) into objects of shame and dismissal. By the end of the decade and the early 1930s, the trials had become weapons for enforcing social and political conformity. Their texts were still fictional—indeed, fantastical—but the actors and the verdicts were now all too real.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTrials (Political crimes and offenses)zSoviet Union. 0aTrials in literature. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171147340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501711473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501711473.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK